<div class="content-section">
  <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>
  <div class="faq-list">
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What blood tests should a man get at 40?</div>
      <div class="faq-answer">Go beyond the standard lipid panel. The essential additions for men at 40: <a href="/biomarkers/apob">ApoB</a>, <a href="/biomarkers/lipoprotein-a">Lp(a)</a> (once), <a href="/biomarkers/fasting-insulin">fasting insulin</a>, <a href="/biomarkers/hscrp">hsCRP</a>, <a href="/biomarkers/homocysteine">homocysteine</a>, free testosterone + SHBG + estradiol, <a href="/biomarkers/psa">PSA baseline</a>, <a href="/biomarkers/vitamin-d">Vitamin D</a>, <a href="/biomarkers/tsh">TSH + free T3/T4</a>, and <a href="/biomarkers/ferritin">ferritin</a>. Most of these are not ordered in standard primary care.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What&#8217;s the difference between total testosterone and free testosterone?</div>
      <div class="faq-answer">Total testosterone measures all testosterone in the blood, including the majority bound to proteins (SHBG and albumin) and biologically unavailable. <a href="/biomarkers/free-testosterone">Free testosterone</a> measures only the active fraction &#8212; roughly 1 to 3 percent. As SHBG rises with age, free testosterone falls even when total testosterone looks normal. Both must be measured together to get an accurate picture of androgenic status in men over 40.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Why is fasting insulin more important than HbA1c for men over 40?</div>
      <div class="faq-answer"><a href="/biomarkers/fasting-insulin">Fasting insulin</a> rises years before HbA1c crosses the prediabetes threshold. A man can have completely normal HbA1c while fasting insulin is already elevated &#8212; a state of early insulin resistance that substantially increases cardiovascular risk. Standard care orders HbA1c; almost no one orders fasting insulin unless diabetes is already suspected.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Should men over 40 check estradiol?</div>
      <div class="faq-answer">Yes &#8212; always when evaluating testosterone. As body fat increases, aromatase activity converts more testosterone to <a href="/biomarkers/estradiol">estradiol</a>. Elevated E2 in men suppresses the HPG axis, further reducing testosterone production. It should always be measured alongside total and free testosterone for a complete hormonal picture.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Should men over 40 get a PSA test?</div>
      <div class="faq-answer">Yes &#8212; for baseline purposes. The value of early PSA testing is establishing a reference point for tracking velocity over subsequent years. A <a href="/biomarkers/psa">PSA</a> that doubles within two years is clinically significant regardless of absolute value. Men with family history of prostate cancer should start earlier.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Do I need a doctor to order these tests?</div>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. Direct-to-consumer services like <a href="/reviews/ulta-lab-tests">Ulta Lab Tests</a> allow any adult to order all of these markers without a physician&#8217;s referral &#8212; you purchase online, visit a Quest Diagnostics draw site, and receive results in 24&#8211;48 hours. Not available in New York, New Jersey, Rhode Island, or Hawaii.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

